      {% if wardrobe_variant == 'sliding' %}
        <h2 class="bw-wardrobe-title">Sliding wardrobes need a cleaner decision path than a normal cupboard purchase</h2>
        <p class="bw-wardrobe-copy">The room should decide the format first, then the shutter system, then the internal rhythm. That order keeps the result usable and visually calm.</p>
      {% elsif wardrobe_variant == 'hinged' %}
        <h2 class="bw-wardrobe-title">Hinged wardrobes work best when access and internal structure are decided together</h2>
        <p class="bw-wardrobe-copy">A hinged wardrobe feels effortless when the front clearance, door count, and storage plan are approved as one decision instead of three separate ones.</p>
      {% elsif wardrobe_variant == 'walk-in' %}
        <h2 class="bw-wardrobe-title">Walk-in wardrobes should feel like a small room, not just a row of storage modules</h2>
        <p class="bw-wardrobe-copy">The strongest walk-in plans define movement, dressing, mirrors, lighting, and storage density before the visual finish takes over.</p>
      {% else %}
        <h2 class="bw-wardrobe-title">Use this page to narrow the wardrobe brief before the estimate conversation starts</h2>
        <p class="bw-wardrobe-copy">Sliding, hinged, and walk-in are solving different problems. This lens helps buyers choose the right path before they compare finishes or ask for pricing.</p>
      {% endif %}
    </div>
    <div class="bw-wardrobe-lens-grid">
      {% if wardrobe_variant == 'sliding' %}
        <article class="bw-wardrobe-lens-card"><span class="bw-wardrobe-lens-step">01</span><h3>Clearance over decoration</h3><p>Sliding is strongest when it solves a real circulation problem in the bedroom, not when it is chosen only for the visual effect.</p></article>
        <article class="bw-wardrobe-lens-card"><span class="bw-wardrobe-lens-step">02</span><h3>Track quality decides daily feel</h3><p>Quiet movement, stable panels, and clean alignment matter more here than they would on a conventional hinged wardrobe.</p></article>
        <article class="bw-wardrobe-lens-card"><span class="bw-wardrobe-lens-step">03</span><h3>Mirror use should stay balanced</h3><p>Mirror-led shutters can visually open the room, but they work best when the reflection pattern supports the bedroom composition.</p></article>
        <article class="bw-wardrobe-lens-card bw-wardrobe-lens-card--accent"><span class="bw-wardrobe-lens-step">04</span><h3>Internal access must be planned bay by bay</h3><p>Because panels move across each other, daily-use storage should be grouped carefully so the wardrobe does not feel awkward later.</p></article>
      {% elsif wardrobe_variant == 'hinged' %}
        <article class="bw-wardrobe-lens-card"><span class="bw-wardrobe-lens-step">01</span><h3>Leave enough swing room</h3><p>Hinged wardrobes stay comfortable only when the bed line, circulation path, and door arc are checked before the elevation is frozen.</p></article>
        <article class="bw-wardrobe-lens-card"><span class="bw-wardrobe-lens-step">02</span><h3>Door rhythm matters</h3><p>Balanced panel widths and better handle placement make the elevation feel deliberate rather than busy.</p></article>
        <article class="bw-wardrobe-lens-card"><span class="bw-wardrobe-lens-step">03</span><h3>Use full visibility well</h3><p>Because the inside is visible at once, drawers, hanging, shelves, and lofts should be mapped as a complete storage system.</p></article>
        <article class="bw-wardrobe-lens-card bw-wardrobe-lens-card--accent"><span class="bw-wardrobe-lens-step">04</span><h3>Hardware is part of the premium finish</h3><p>Soft-close hinges, strong alignment, and a calm handle strategy contribute to the feel buyers notice every day.</p></article>
      {% elsif wardrobe_variant == 'walk-in' %}
        <article class="bw-wardrobe-lens-card"><span class="bw-wardrobe-lens-step">01</span><h3>Think in room zones</h3><p>Walk-ins work best when storage, dressing, mirrors, and movement are all part of one room layout rather than separate units.</p></article>
        <article class="bw-wardrobe-lens-card"><span class="bw-wardrobe-lens-step">02</span><h3>Control the open and closed mix</h3><p>Open shelves create lightness, while closed sections keep the room tidy. The best design uses both with intent.</p></article>
        <article class="bw-wardrobe-lens-card"><span class="bw-wardrobe-lens-step">03</span><h3>Lighting should be planned early</h3><p>Mirror placement, task lighting, and visibility at the dressing point all influence whether the room feels calm or awkward.</p></article>
        <article class="bw-wardrobe-lens-card bw-wardrobe-lens-card--accent"><span class="bw-wardrobe-lens-step">04</span><h3>Consultation should happen sooner</h3><p>Walk-ins are room-scale projects. The estimate conversation becomes more useful once the zones and dresser intent are clear.</p></article>
      {% else %}
        <article class="bw-wardrobe-lens-card"><span class="bw-wardrobe-lens-step">01</span><h3>Room-fit decides the format</h3><p>Bedroom width, bed position, and clearance will usually tell you whether sliding, hinged, or walk-in is the right first choice.</p></article>
        <article class="bw-wardrobe-lens-card"><span class="bw-wardrobe-lens-step">02</span><h3>Storage mix comes next</h3><p>Hanging, folded items, drawers, seasonal storage, and accessories should be listed before the wardrobe looks are finalized.</p></article>
        <article class="bw-wardrobe-lens-card"><span class="bw-wardrobe-lens-step">03</span><h3>Finish after function</h3><p>Mirror ratio, wood tones, matte fronts, and hardware should support the room rather than drive the whole decision too early.</p></article>
        <article class="bw-wardrobe-lens-card bw-wardrobe-lens-card--accent"><span class="bw-wardrobe-lens-step">04</span><h3>Use the calculator when the brief feels real</h3><p>The wardrobe calculator and estimate flow become far more useful once the customer has already narrowed the format and storage intent.</p></article>
      {% endif %}
    </div>
    <div class="bw-wardrobe-lens-actions">
      <a class="bw-wardrobe-lens-link" href="{{ calculator_cta_url }}">Open Wardrobe Calculator</a>
      <button class="bw-wardrobe-button--secondary" type="button" data-bw-wardrobe-estimate-open data-estimate-trigger="lens">Get Free Estimate</button>
      <a class="bw-wardrobe-button--secondary" href="{{ contact_url }}">Talk To Bluewud</a>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="bw-wardrobe-block">
    <div class="bw-wardrobe-head">
      <span class="bw-wardrobe-eyebrow">Planning guidance</span>
      {% if wardrobe_variant == 'sliding' %}
        <h2 class="bw-wardrobe-title">Sliding wardrobes feel premium only when clearance, tracks, and internals are planned together</h2>
        <p class="bw-wardrobe-copy">The format solves a real bedroom problem, but it also introduces track, mirror, and access decisions that should be settled before the front elevation is approved.</p>
      {% elsif wardrobe_variant == 'hinged' %}
        <h2 class="bw-wardrobe-title">Hinged wardrobes work best when access, panel widths, and room clearance are resolved early</h2>
        <p class="bw-wardrobe-copy">They are intuitive and highly practical, but the best hinged wardrobes still depend on better panel planning, better internals, and enough room in front.</p>
      {% elsif wardrobe_variant == 'walk-in' %}
        <h2 class="bw-wardrobe-title">Walk-in wardrobes need zoning, not just cabinetry</h2>
        <p class="bw-wardrobe-copy">This format becomes premium when storage, dressing, mirrors, lighting, and movement are treated like one integrated room plan rather than a row of cabinets.</p>
      {% else %}
        <h2 class="bw-wardrobe-title">The right wardrobe starts with room-fit, not just the shutter style</h2>
        <p class="bw-wardrobe-copy">A more substantial landing page should help buyers settle format, room clearance, storage mix, and finish direction before they are asked for a final estimate.</p>
      {% endif %}
    </div>
    <div class="bw-wardrobe-grid-4">
      {% if wardrobe_variant == 'sliding' %}
        <article class="bw-wardrobe-card"><span class="bw-wardrobe-card-label">01</span><h3>Check the bed line first</h3><p>Sliding works well when the wardrobe sits close to the bed and there is not enough room for swinging shutters.</p></article>
        <article class="bw-wardrobe-card"><span class="bw-wardrobe-card-label">02</span><h3>Plan the track and panel width</h3><p>A refined sliding wardrobe depends on smoother tracks, sensible panel proportions, and controlled shutter weight.</p></article>
        <article class="bw-wardrobe-card"><span class="bw-wardrobe-card-label">03</span><h3>Design around partial access</h3><p>Because all compartments do not open together, drawers and daily-use shelves should be grouped carefully.</p></article>
        <article class="bw-wardrobe-card"><span class="bw-wardrobe-card-label">04</span><h3>Use mirrors with restraint</h3><p>Mirror-led sliding shutters can enlarge compact bedrooms, but they should support the room composition rather than dominate it.</p></article>
      {% elsif wardrobe_variant == 'hinged' %}
        <article class="bw-wardrobe-card"><span class="bw-wardrobe-card-label">01</span><h3>Protect the front clearance</h3><p>Hinged wardrobes feel effortless only when there is enough door swing space between the bed and the wardrobe line.</p></article>
        <article class="bw-wardrobe-card"><span class="bw-wardrobe-card-label">02</span><h3>Get the panel widths right</h3><p>Well-balanced shutters, cleaner handle placement, and a disciplined door count make the wardrobe feel more premium.</p></article>
        <article class="bw-wardrobe-card"><span class="bw-wardrobe-card-label">03</span><h3>Use full access properly</h3><p>The advantage is complete visibility, so drawers, shelves, lockable units, and hanging lengths should all be scoped upfront.</p></article>
        <article class="bw-wardrobe-card"><span class="bw-wardrobe-card-label">04</span><h3>Let hardware carry the experience</h3><p>Soft-close hinges, good handles, and tighter alignment matter as much as the carcass when the shutters are opened every day.</p></article>
      {% elsif wardrobe_variant == 'walk-in' %}
        <article class="bw-wardrobe-card"><span class="bw-wardrobe-card-label">01</span><h3>Zone the room deliberately</h3><p>Walk-ins should separate hanging, folded storage, drawers, mirrors, and dressing rather than repeating one storage type everywhere.</p></article>
        <article class="bw-wardrobe-card"><span class="bw-wardrobe-card-label">02</span><h3>Balance open and closed storage</h3><p>Too much open shelving can feel messy, while too much closed storage makes the room feel heavy. The mix should be purposeful.</p></article>
        <article class="bw-wardrobe-card"><span class="bw-wardrobe-card-label">03</span><h3>Plan lighting and mirrors early</h3><p>Premium walk-ins feel calmer when task lighting, full-length mirrors, and dressing visibility are decided before joinery details.</p></article>
        <article class="bw-wardrobe-card"><span class="bw-wardrobe-card-label">04</span><h3>Think like a room planner</h3><p>This is closer to designing a suite environment than buying one wardrobe, so early estimate and consultation matter more.</p></article>
      {% else %}
        <article class="bw-wardrobe-card"><span class="bw-wardrobe-card-label">01</span><h3>Start with room-fit and movement</h3><p>Bedroom width, bed placement, window lines, and circulation decide whether sliding, hinged, or walk-in is the right first direction.</p></article>
        <article class="bw-wardrobe-card"><span class="bw-wardrobe-card-label">02</span><h3>Choose the opening style first</h3><p>Customers make better decisions when the access format is locked before mirror panels, textures, or colour schemes are discussed.</p></article>
        <article class="bw-wardrobe-card"><span class="bw-wardrobe-card-label">03</span><h3>Write the storage brief early</h3><p>Long hanging, folded stacks, drawers, valuables, accessories, and loft storage should all be scoped before elevation styling begins.</p></article>
        <article class="bw-wardrobe-card"><span class="bw-wardrobe-card-label">04</span><h3>Price with intent, not guesswork</h3><p>Dimensions, material tier, shutter style, mirror use, and accessories move the estimate much more meaningfully than mood alone.</p></article>
      {% endif %}
    </div>
  </section>

