      <article class="bw-wardrobe-card"><span class="bw-wardrobe-card-label">Material</span><h3>Plywood versus engineered wood</h3><p>Engineered wood keeps the budget disciplined, while plywood-led upgrades usually suit buyers expecting a more premium long-term build.</p></article>
      <article class="bw-wardrobe-card"><span class="bw-wardrobe-card-label">Hardware</span><h3>{% if wardrobe_variant == 'sliding' %}Tracks, rollers, and channel feel{% elsif wardrobe_variant == 'hinged' %}Hinges, soft close, and handle feel{% elsif wardrobe_variant == 'walk-in' %}Open shelving rhythm and hardware restraint{% else %}Opening hardware and daily feel{% endif %}</h3><p>{% if wardrobe_variant == 'sliding' %}Sliding wardrobes reveal poor hardware quickly, so track smoothness and shutter movement should never feel secondary.{% elsif wardrobe_variant == 'hinged' %}Hinged wardrobes are touched constantly, so hinge quality and handle ergonomics become part of the premium experience.{% elsif wardrobe_variant == 'walk-in' %}Walk-ins benefit from quieter detailing so shelves, drawers, and visible edges feel deliberate instead of visually noisy.{% else %}The opening system is what the user feels every day, so hardware quality should be scoped as carefully as the finish.{% endif %}</p></article>
