      <span class="bw-wardrobe-eyebrow">Measurement and space guide</span>
      {% if wardrobe_variant == 'sliding' %}
        <h2 class="bw-wardrobe-title">Sliding wardrobes need the room width, track line, and bay access decided together</h2>
        <p class="bw-wardrobe-copy">This guide keeps the decision grounded in the actual bedroom so the estimate can reflect clearance, access, and panel rhythm rather than only the visual elevation.</p>
      {% elsif wardrobe_variant == 'hinged' %}
        <h2 class="bw-wardrobe-title">Hinged wardrobes feel better when front clearance and door rhythm are measured early</h2>
        <p class="bw-wardrobe-copy">The stronger hinged wardrobe brief starts with swing clearance, then moves to bay count, then to inside storage depth and hardware comfort.</p>
      {% elsif wardrobe_variant == 'walk-in' %}
        <h2 class="bw-wardrobe-title">Walk-in wardrobes should be measured like a small room, not a cabinet line</h2>
        <p class="bw-wardrobe-copy">This format becomes more useful when circulation, dressing point, mirror position, and storage zoning are mapped before pricing or finishes are discussed.</p>
      {% else %}
        <h2 class="bw-wardrobe-title">A better wardrobe brief begins with room fit, access, and what the wardrobe must store</h2>
        <p class="bw-wardrobe-copy">These checkpoints help the customer settle the practical side of the project first, so the calculator and estimate can feel more grounded.</p>
      {% endif %}
    </div>
    <div class="bw-wardrobe-measure-grid">
      {% if wardrobe_variant == 'sliding' %}
        <article class="bw-wardrobe-measure-card"><span class="bw-wardrobe-measure-step">01</span><h3>Check wall width first</h3><p>Sliding wardrobes work best when the wall line is measured precisely and the panel spans are planned around the actual room width.</p></article>
        <article class="bw-wardrobe-measure-card"><span class="bw-wardrobe-measure-step">02</span><h3>Confirm track depth</h3><p>The track and shutter stack need enough allowance so the wardrobe remains smooth, stable, and visually disciplined.</p></article>
        <article class="bw-wardrobe-measure-card"><span class="bw-wardrobe-measure-step">03</span><h3>Protect the usable bays</h3><p>Place the daily-use storage in the most accessible sections, because the panels will always overlap part of the interior.</p></article>
        <article class="bw-wardrobe-measure-card bw-wardrobe-measure-card--accent"><span class="bw-wardrobe-measure-step">04</span><h3>Plan mirror and finish width</h3><p>Reflective or feature panels should be balanced against the room so the wardrobe feels premium without taking over the wall.</p></article>
      {% elsif wardrobe_variant == 'hinged' %}
        <article class="bw-wardrobe-measure-card"><span class="bw-wardrobe-measure-step">01</span><h3>Measure the swing space</h3><p>Hinged wardrobes need the front clearance checked against the bed, side tables, and circulation path before anything else is locked.</p></article>
        <article class="bw-wardrobe-measure-card"><span class="bw-wardrobe-measure-step">02</span><h3>Count the door rhythm</h3><p>Panel count and door widths affect how the wardrobe feels in daily use, so the elevation should stay proportionate and calm.</p></article>
        <article class="bw-wardrobe-measure-card"><span class="bw-wardrobe-measure-step">03</span><h3>Write the inside brief</h3><p>Full access is the real advantage here, which means hanging, drawers, shelves, and lofts should be mapped as one complete storage plan.</p></article>
        <article class="bw-wardrobe-measure-card bw-wardrobe-measure-card--accent"><span class="bw-wardrobe-measure-step">04</span><h3>Leave room for handles and hardware</h3><p>Handle projection, hinge quality, and shutter weight can change the final feel more than buyers usually expect during early planning.</p></article>
      {% elsif wardrobe_variant == 'walk-in' %}
        <article class="bw-wardrobe-measure-card"><span class="bw-wardrobe-measure-step">01</span><h3>Map circulation early</h3><p>Walk-in wardrobes feel premium when movement around the room stays comfortable and the dressing path is not blocked by storage.</p></article>
        <article class="bw-wardrobe-measure-card"><span class="bw-wardrobe-measure-step">02</span><h3>Place the dressing point</h3><p>The mirror, bench, or dresser should sit where it actually helps the user prepare, not where there is leftover space.</p></article>
        <article class="bw-wardrobe-measure-card"><span class="bw-wardrobe-measure-step">03</span><h3>Balance closed and open storage</h3><p>Open shelving brings lightness, while concealed storage keeps the room orderly. The balance should be intentional from the start.</p></article>
        <article class="bw-wardrobe-measure-card bw-wardrobe-measure-card--accent"><span class="bw-wardrobe-measure-step">04</span><h3>Think like a room planner</h3><p>Once walk-in planning is treated like a room strategy, the estimate becomes much more accurate and the final result feels more composed.</p></article>
      {% else %}
        <article class="bw-wardrobe-measure-card"><span class="bw-wardrobe-measure-step">01</span><h3>Measure the wall and ceiling height</h3><p>Width, height, and any loft condition are the first things needed to understand the project shape properly.</p></article>
        <article class="bw-wardrobe-measure-card"><span class="bw-wardrobe-measure-step">02</span><h3>Decide the opening style</h3><p>Sliding, hinged, or walk-in should be selected before the front styling starts, because each one changes how the room works.</p></article>
        <article class="bw-wardrobe-measure-card"><span class="bw-wardrobe-measure-step">03</span><h3>List what must be stored</h3><p>Clothes, bags, bedding, accessories, and valuables all need different internal treatment, and that impacts the estimate.</p></article>
        <article class="bw-wardrobe-measure-card bw-wardrobe-measure-card--accent"><span class="bw-wardrobe-measure-step">04</span><h3>Keep the estimate ready</h3><p>Once the customer has the room size and storage list, the calculator and estimate flow can move much faster and with less rework.</p></article>
      {% endif %}
    </div>
    <div class="bw-wardrobe-measure-actions">
      <a class="bw-wardrobe-measure-link" href="{{ calculator_cta_url }}">Open Wardrobe Calculator</a>
      <button class="bw-wardrobe-button--secondary" type="button" data-bw-wardrobe-estimate-open data-estimate-trigger="measure">Get Free Estimate</button>
      <a class="bw-wardrobe-button--secondary" href="{{ contact_url }}">Talk To Bluewud</a>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="bw-wardrobe-block">
    <div class="bw-wardrobe-head">
      <span class="bw-wardrobe-eyebrow">Internals and utility</span>
      <h2 class="bw-wardrobe-title">What should be planned inside the wardrobe before the outside is approved</h2>
      <p class="bw-wardrobe-copy">A wardrobe is won internally before it becomes visually impressive. The better the inside is planned, the less quickly the bedroom falls back into clutter.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="bw-wardrobe-grid-3">
      <article class="bw-wardrobe-card"><span class="bw-wardrobe-card-label">Hanging</span><h3>Long hanging and short hanging</h3><p>Use separate hanging lengths for sarees, dresses, shirts, jackets, and daily office wear so valuable height is not wasted.</p></article>
      <article class="bw-wardrobe-card"><span class="bw-wardrobe-card-label">Shelves</span><h3>Folded stacks that stay usable</h3><p>Shelf widths and spacing should support real folded habits rather than turning every shelf into one deep, unreachable pile.</p></article>
      <article class="bw-wardrobe-card"><span class="bw-wardrobe-card-label">Drawers</span><h3>Drawer banks and trays for small essentials</h3><p>Jewellery, watches, accessories, undergarments, grooming items, and smaller valuables usually need better drawer planning than buyers expect.</p></article>
      <article class="bw-wardrobe-card"><span class="bw-wardrobe-card-label">Seasonal</span><h3>Lofts and upper storage for low-frequency items</h3><p>Suitcases, winter layers, extra bedding, and festive pieces belong higher up so the daily-use sections stay calmer.</p></article>
      <article class="bw-wardrobe-card"><span class="bw-wardrobe-card-label">Security</span><h3>Safe zones and private compartments</h3><p>Lockboxes, hidden drawers, and restricted compartments should be scoped early rather than awkwardly inserted at the end.</p></article>
      <article class="bw-wardrobe-card"><span class="bw-wardrobe-card-label">Accessories</span><h3>Trouser racks, pull-outs, mirrors, and convenience add-ons</h3><p>Accessories can meaningfully improve daily use, but they should support the lifestyle rather than inflate the project without purpose.</p></article>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="bw-wardrobe-block">
    <div class="bw-wardrobe-head">
      <span class="bw-wardrobe-eyebrow">Estimate guidance</span>
      <h2 class="bw-wardrobe-title">What changes the wardrobe estimate the most</h2>
      <p class="bw-wardrobe-copy">A stronger landing page should explain what moves the number before the buyer reaches out, so the estimate feels informed instead of random.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="bw-wardrobe-grid-4">
      <article class="bw-wardrobe-card"><span class="bw-wardrobe-card-label">Size</span><h3>Width, height, and loft scope</h3><p>The footprint of the wardrobe, the ceiling intent, and the loft strategy shape both material volume and installation complexity.</p></article>
      <article class="bw-wardrobe-card"><span class="bw-wardrobe-card-label">Tier</span><h3>Carcass material and build level</h3><p>Material direction is one of the clearest budget shifts, especially when buyers move from base engineered systems toward premium builds.</p></article>
      <article class="bw-wardrobe-card"><span class="bw-wardrobe-card-label">Front</span><h3>Shutter style, mirrors, and finish mix</h3><p>Mirror use, glass, matte shutters, acrylic faces, and feature panels all affect the number and the perceived luxury of the wardrobe.</p></article>
      <article class="bw-wardrobe-card"><span class="bw-wardrobe-card-label">Add-ons</span><h3>Accessories, lighting, and site conditions</h3><p>Drawer systems, trays, speciality hardware, lighting, and trickier site constraints often explain why two similar wardrobes price differently.</p></article>
    </div>
  </section>

  {% if is_collection_context %}
    <section class="bw-wardrobe-block bw-wardrobe-calculator-anchor" id="wardrobe-calculator">
      <div class="bw-wardrobe-embedded-calculator">
        <div class="bw-wardrobe-embedded-calculator__head">
          <span class="bw-wardrobe-embedded-calculator__eyebrow">Wardrobe calculator</span>
          <h2 class="bw-wardrobe-embedded-calculator__title">Review the wardrobe brief here without leaving the wardrobe page</h2>
          <p class="bw-wardrobe-embedded-calculator__copy">On the collection page, this embedded calculator keeps the wardrobe journey visible and reviewable. It is the same consultation-first wardrobe workflow, placed lower on the page so the planning context stays together.</p>
        </div>
        {% render 'wardrobe-calculator-content' %}
      </div>
    </section>
  {% endif %}

  <section class="bw-wardrobe-band">
    <div class="bw-wardrobe-head">
      <span class="bw-wardrobe-eyebrow">Move from inspiration to planning</span>
      {% if wardrobe_variant == 'all' %}
        <h2 class="bw-wardrobe-title">Narrow the format, then ask for the estimate</h2>
        <p class="bw-wardrobe-copy">The strongest next step is a directional price path once the wardrobe type, internal brief, and finish direction feel clear enough to discuss seriously.</p>
      {% else %}
        <h2 class="bw-wardrobe-title">Turn this wardrobe direction into a real estimate</h2>
        <p class="bw-wardrobe-copy">Once the room fit, internal intent, and finish direction feel right, the calculator and estimate flow can move the project forward with much less confusion.</p>
      {% endif %}
    </div>
    <div class="bw-wardrobe-actions">
      <a class="bw-wardrobe-button" href="{{ calculator_cta_url }}">Open Wardrobe Calculator</a>
      <button class="bw-wardrobe-button--secondary" type="button" data-bw-wardrobe-estimate-open data-estimate-trigger="band">Get Free Estimate</button>
      <a class="bw-wardrobe-button--secondary" href="{{ contact_url }}">Talk To Bluewud</a>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="bw-wardrobe-block">
    <div class="bw-wardrobe-head">
      <span class="bw-wardrobe-eyebrow">Live wardrobe directions</span>
      {% if wardrobe_variant == 'all' %}
        <h2 class="bw-wardrobe-title">Browse live wardrobe directions after the planning brief is clear</h2>
        <p class="bw-wardrobe-copy">This section keeps the landing page tied to the real Bluewud catalog, so the guidance above flows into actual wardrobe designs that can be shortlisted and discussed.</p>
      {% elsif wardrobe_variant == 'sliding' %}
        <h2 class="bw-wardrobe-title">Browse live sliding wardrobe directions from the catalog</h2>
        <p class="bw-wardrobe-copy">Use the store range to compare front treatments, mirror use, tone palettes, and practical sliding layouts before asking for an estimate.</p>
      {% elsif wardrobe_variant == 'hinged' %}
        <h2 class="bw-wardrobe-title">Browse live hinged wardrobe directions from the catalog</h2>
        <p class="bw-wardrobe-copy">These product references help narrow shutter style, loft treatment, and internal rhythm so the estimate conversation starts with a stronger brief.</p>
      {% else %}
        <h2 class="bw-wardrobe-title">Browse live walk-in wardrobe directions from the catalog</h2>
        <p class="bw-wardrobe-copy">Review wardrobe rooms, open sections, and premium detailing cues here before locking in the exact walk-in scope with Bluewud.</p>
      {% endif %}
    </div>
    <div class="bw-wardrobe-products">
      {% assign shown = 0 %}
      {% if wardrobe_collection != blank %}
        {% for product in wardrobe_collection.products %}
          {% assign include_product = false %}
          {% assign product_title_downcase = product.title | downcase %}
          {% if wardrobe_variant == 'all' %}
            {% assign include_product = true %}
          {% elsif wardrobe_variant == 'walk-in' %}
            {% if product_title_downcase contains 'walk in' or product_title_downcase contains 'walk-in' %}
              {% assign include_product = true %}
            {% endif %}
          {% elsif keyword != blank and product_title_downcase contains keyword %}
            {% assign include_product = true %}
          {% endif %}
          {% if include_product %}
            <a class="bw-wardrobe-product" href="{{ product.url }}">
              <div class="bw-wardrobe-product-media">
                {% if product.featured_image %}
                  {{ product.featured_image | image_url: width: 900 | image_tag: loading: 'lazy', widths: '360, 540, 720, 900', sizes: '(max-width: 720px) 100vw, 33vw', alt: product.title }}
                {% endif %}
              </div>
              <div>
                <h3>{{ product.title }}</h3>
                <p>
                  {% if product.metafields.my_fields.product_subtitle != blank %}
                    {{ product.metafields.my_fields.product_subtitle }}
                  {% else %}
                    Premium wardrobe storage with cleaner organization and better bedroom rhythm.
                  {% endif %}
                </p>
              </div>
              <span>View Design</span>
            </a>
            {% assign shown = shown | plus: 1 %}
          {% endif %}
          {% if shown == 6 %}
            {% break %}
          {% endif %}
        {% endfor %}
      {% endif %}
      {% if shown == 0 %}
        <article class="bw-wardrobe-card"><h3>Sliding Wardrobes</h3><p>For compact bedrooms and cleaner front clearance.</p></article>
        <article class="bw-wardrobe-card"><h3>Hinged Wardrobes</h3><p>For complete access and more classic everyday usability.</p></article>
        <article class="bw-wardrobe-card"><h3>Walk-in Wardrobes</h3><p>For larger premium bedrooms and suite-style organization.</p></article>
      {% endif %}
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="bw-wardrobe-block">
    <div class="bw-wardrobe-head">
      <span class="bw-wardrobe-eyebrow">Questions to settle early</span>
      {% if wardrobe_variant == 'all' %}
        <h2 class="bw-wardrobe-title">The wardrobe questions worth answering before you ask for pricing</h2>
        <p class="bw-wardrobe-copy">A stronger brief almost always produces a better design conversation. These are the practical questions premium buyers usually need to settle early.</p>
      {% elsif wardrobe_variant == 'sliding' %}
        <h2 class="bw-wardrobe-title">Sliding wardrobe questions that matter before design freeze</h2>
        <p class="bw-wardrobe-copy">Sliding wardrobes look minimal when the details are planned properly. These questions help avoid the common layout and usability misses.</p>
      {% elsif wardrobe_variant == 'hinged' %}
        <h2 class="bw-wardrobe-title">Hinged wardrobe questions that shape the final outcome</h2>
        <p class="bw-wardrobe-copy">Hinged wardrobes feel effortless when the door swing, internal access, and finish detailing are decided early rather than corrected later.</p>
      {% else %}
        <h2 class="bw-wardrobe-title">Walk-in wardrobe questions to settle before moving into execution</h2>
        <p class="bw-wardrobe-copy">Walk-in spaces need stronger scope control than standard wardrobes. These answers help turn aspiration into a workable premium brief.</p>
      {% endif %}
    </div>
    <div class="bw-wardrobe-grid-2">
      {% if wardrobe_variant == 'all' %}
        <article class="bw-wardrobe-faq"><h3>How do I decide between sliding, hinged, and walk-in?</h3><p>Start with the room footprint and how you move through the bedroom daily. Sliding is efficient in tighter rooms, hinged gives full visual access, and walk-in only makes sense when the bedroom can support a dedicated dressing zone.</p></article>
        <article class="bw-wardrobe-faq"><h3>What usually changes wardrobe pricing the most?</h3><p>Overall dimensions, carcass and shutter material, finish category, mirror area, internal accessories, drawer count, and installation complexity move the estimate most sharply.</p></article>
        <article class="bw-wardrobe-faq"><h3>Should internals be planned before the look is approved?</h3><p>Yes. Hanging lengths, folded zones, valuables, bags, seasonal storage, laundry, and mirror placement should be discussed before the elevation is finalized, or the wardrobe risks looking premium without working properly.</p></article>
        <article class="bw-wardrobe-faq"><h3>What details should be ready before I speak to Bluewud?</h3><p>Bring rough room width and height, a sense of wardrobe type, preferred finish direction, and a realistic list of what needs to be stored. That shortens the path to a useful estimate.</p></article>
        <article class="bw-wardrobe-faq"><h3>Can one wardrobe include lofts, dressers, or open display zones?</h3><p>Yes. Most premium wardrobes need a mix of closed storage, drawers, accessories, mirrors, and sometimes a small open feature zone. The key is balancing utility with a cleaner front composition.</p></article>
        <article class="bw-wardrobe-faq"><h3>What is the cleanest next step from this page?</h3><p>Use the wardrobe calculator for directional pricing, shortlist the nearest layout direction, and then open the estimate form with your room brief while the requirements are still clear.</p></article>
      {% elsif wardrobe_variant == 'sliding' %}
        <article class="bw-wardrobe-faq"><h3>When is a sliding wardrobe the better choice?</h3><p>Sliding works best when bedroom clearance is tight, the front elevation needs to stay visually calm, or a broader uninterrupted wardrobe face suits the room better than opening shutters.</p></article>
        <article class="bw-wardrobe-faq"><h3>Do sliding wardrobes reduce usable storage?</h3><p>Not necessarily, but they need smarter internal zoning because one bay is always partially covered. The internal plan matters more than the elevation.</p></article>
        <article class="bw-wardrobe-faq"><h3>What finish decisions matter most on sliding shutters?</h3><p>Mirror ratio, panel segmentation, track quality, handle profile, and whether the shutter language feels warm, minimal, or more decorative will define the final look.</p></article>
        <article class="bw-wardrobe-faq"><h3>Can a sliding wardrobe still feel premium in smaller bedrooms?</h3><p>Yes. Clean paneling, well-balanced mirrors, refined laminate or glass choices, and disciplined internal planning often make sliding wardrobes feel more premium in compact rooms than bulkier hinged options.</p></article>
        <article class="bw-wardrobe-faq"><h3>What should I prepare before asking for a sliding estimate?</h3><p>Keep the wall width, floor-to-ceiling height, preferred shutter look, and internal storage priorities ready so the quote direction matches the room from the start.</p></article>
        <article class="bw-wardrobe-faq"><h3>What is the fastest next step from here?</h3><p>Review the calculator for directional pricing, shortlist the closest sliding design cue from the product grid, and then open the estimate form with that reference in mind.</p></article>
      {% elsif wardrobe_variant == 'hinged' %}
        <article class="bw-wardrobe-faq"><h3>Why do many buyers still prefer hinged wardrobes?</h3><p>Hinged wardrobes offer full-bay visibility, easy internal access, and more flexibility for drawers, mirrors, and loft treatment. They remain the most familiar and forgiving wardrobe format.</p></article>
        <article class="bw-wardrobe-faq"><h3>What needs extra care in hinged wardrobe planning?</h3><p>Door swing clearance, handle choice, shutter weight, loft alignment, and how the wardrobe opens near beds or side tables should be settled before design approval.</p></article>
        <article class="bw-wardrobe-faq"><h3>How do I make a hinged wardrobe look more premium?</h3><p>Cleaner proportions, better shutter detailing, premium laminates or acrylics, integrated mirrors, sharper hardware, and a composed internal layout usually matter more than adding visual noise.</p></article>
        <article class="bw-wardrobe-faq"><h3>Are hinged wardrobes better for internal organization?</h3><p>Often yes, because every bay becomes fully visible at once. That makes it easier to mix hanging, drawers, shelves, accessories, and loft storage without compromise.</p></article>
        <article class="bw-wardrobe-faq"><h3>What should be ready before asking for a hinged estimate?</h3><p>Keep the rough wall dimensions, desired door look, loft requirement, internal storage list, and any mirror or dresser add-ons ready before opening the estimate flow.</p></article>
        <article class="bw-wardrobe-faq"><h3>What is the next best step from this page?</h3><p>Use the calculator to anchor the budget, review live hinged references below, and then raise an estimate request once the storage brief feels complete enough.</p></article>
      {% else %}
        <article class="bw-wardrobe-faq"><h3>When does a walk-in wardrobe make practical sense?</h3><p>A walk-in is justified when the bedroom can support a dedicated dressing zone with comfortable circulation, layered storage, and enough usable depth to avoid becoming just an expensive passage.</p></article>
        <article class="bw-wardrobe-faq"><h3>What usually gets missed in early walk-in planning?</h3><p>Lighting, mirror placement, open versus closed storage balance, island or dresser feasibility, and how daily categories are zoned across the room are often underplanned at the start.</p></article>
        <article class="bw-wardrobe-faq"><h3>Should a walk-in be fully open or partially shuttered?</h3><p>Most premium walk-ins benefit from a controlled mix. Open sections keep the room lighter, while shuttered storage protects folded clothes, luggage, valuables, and less display-worthy items.</p></article>
        <article class="bw-wardrobe-faq"><h3>What drives the budget on a walk-in wardrobe most?</h3><p>Total room coverage, material quality, glass or mirror usage, drawers and accessories, lighting integration, and whether the space includes vanity or dresser elements all affect pricing.</p></article>
        <article class="bw-wardrobe-faq"><h3>What should I gather before asking for a walk-in estimate?</h3><p>Share the room dimensions, any rough zoning idea, the balance of open and closed storage you prefer, and whether the space must include mirrors, seating, or dresser functionality.</p></article>
        <article class="bw-wardrobe-faq"><h3>How should I move forward from here?</h3><p>Use the pricing path for directional clarity, review live walk-in references below, and then open the estimate flow with a room brief rather than only a style reference.</p></article>
      {% endif %}
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="bw-wardrobe-band">
    <div class="bw-wardrobe-head">
      <span class="bw-wardrobe-eyebrow">Need a real conversation?</span>
      {% if wardrobe_variant == 'all' %}
        <h2 class="bw-wardrobe-title">Start the Bluewud estimate once the wardrobe direction feels clear enough</h2>
        <p class="bw-wardrobe-copy">You do not need a finished design before starting the conversation. A rough room brief, a likely wardrobe format, and the storage priorities above are enough to move into the estimate flow properly.</p>
      {% elsif wardrobe_variant == 'sliding' %}
        <h2 class="bw-wardrobe-title">Move the sliding wardrobe brief into a real Bluewud estimate</h2>
        <p class="bw-wardrobe-copy">Once the room dimensions, shutter look, and internal intent feel mostly locked, the estimate flow becomes the fastest way to turn the direction into a live project conversation.</p>
      {% elsif wardrobe_variant == 'hinged' %}
        <h2 class="bw-wardrobe-title">Move the hinged wardrobe brief into a real Bluewud estimate</h2>
        <p class="bw-wardrobe-copy">If the door style, loft need, and storage mix are broadly clear, the estimate flow is the right next step instead of continuing to browse without a room-led brief.</p>
      {% else %}
        <h2 class="bw-wardrobe-title">Move the walk-in wardrobe brief into a real Bluewud estimate</h2>
        <p class="bw-wardrobe-copy">Walk-in projects benefit from an earlier design conversation. Once the room scope and zoning idea are in place, start the estimate so the concept can be grounded in execution.</p>
      {% endif %}
    </div>
    <div class="bw-wardrobe-actions">
      <button class="bw-wardrobe-button" type="button" data-bw-wardrobe-estimate-open data-estimate-trigger="cta">Get Free Estimate</button>
      <a class="bw-wardrobe-button--secondary" href="{{ phone_url }}">Call Bluewud</a>
      <a class="bw-wardrobe-button--secondary" href="{{ calculator_cta_url }}">Price It First</a>
    </div>
  </section>
</div>

{% render 'modular-estimate-popup', modal_id: 'bw-wardrobe-estimate-popup', modal_title: 'Get a wardrobe estimate', context_label: 'Bluewud modular wardrobe' %}

<script>
  (function () {
    var root = document.querySelector('[data-bw-wardrobe-page]');
    var modal = document.getElementById('bw-wardrobe-estimate-popup');
    if (!root || !modal) return;

    var summaryText = modal.querySelector('[data-bw-estimate-summary-text]');
    var summaryInput = modal.querySelector('[data-bw-estimate-summary-input]');
    var contextInput = modal.querySelector('[data-bw-estimate-context-input]');
    var sourceInput = modal.querySelector('[data-bw-estimate-source-input]');
    var chips = Array.prototype.slice.call(root.querySelectorAll('[data-wardrobe-chip]'));

    function setCurrentChip(key) {
      chips.forEach(function (chip) {
        var isCurrent = chip.getAttribute('data-wardrobe-chip') === key;
        chip.classList.toggle('is-current', isCurrent);
        chip.classList.toggle('is-active', isCurrent);
        if (isCurrent) chip.setAttribute('aria-current', 'page');
        else chip.removeAttribute('aria-current');
      });
    }

    function chipFromHash() {
      var params = new URLSearchParams(window.location.search);
      var hash = (window.location.hash || '').replace('#', '');
      if (hash === 'sliding-wardrobe') return 'sliding';
      if (hash === 'hinged-wardrobe') return 'hinged';
      if (hash === 'walk-in-wardrobe') return 'walk-in';
      if (hash === 'wardrobe-calculator') return 'calculator';
      var type = (params.get('type') || '').toLowerCase();
      if (type === 'sliding') return 'sliding';
      if (type === 'hinged') return 'hinged';
      if (type === 'walk-in' || type === 'walk in') return 'walk-in';
      return 'all';
    }
    function wardrobeTypeForCalculator() {
      var chip = chipFromHash();
      if (chip === 'calculator') {
        var activeChip = root.querySelector('[data-wardrobe-chip].is-current');
        chip = activeChip ? activeChip.getAttribute('data-wardrobe-chip') : 'all';
      }
      return chip === 'calculator' ? 'all' : chip;
    }

    function closeModal() {
      modal.classList.remove('is-open');
      document.body.classList.remove('bw-header-drawer-open');
    }

    function activeVariant() {
      var currentChip = root.querySelector('[data-wardrobe-chip].is-current');
      return currentChip ? currentChip.textContent.trim() : 'All Wardrobes';
    }
    function buildPlanningPayload(trigger) {
      return {
        projectType: 'Modular Wardrobe',
        projectContext: 'Bluewud modular wardrobe',
        referenceSource: ['Modular Wardrobe Guide', activeVariant(), trigger || 'direct'].join(' | '),
        projectRoute: window.location.pathname + window.location.search + (window.location.hash || ''),
        selectedBrief: ['Project: Modular Wardrobe', 'Selected type: ' + activeVariant(), 'Source: ' + (trigger || 'direct')].join(' | '),
        selectedOptions: {
          wardrobe_type: activeVariant(),
          wardrobe_key: chipFromHash(),
          source_trigger: trigger || 'direct',
          page_family: 'modular-wardrobe-guide'
        },
        trigger: trigger || 'direct'
      };
    }
    function persistPlanningPayload(trigger) {
      var payload = buildPlanningPayload(trigger);
      if (window.BluewudProjectBriefStore) {
        window.BluewudProjectBriefStore.save(payload);
      }
      return payload;
    }

    function openModal(trigger) {
      var payload = persistPlanningPayload(trigger);
      if (window.BluewudProjectBriefStore) {
        window.BluewudProjectBriefStore.fillModal(modal, payload);
      } else {
        summaryText.textContent = payload.selectedBrief;
        summaryInput.value = payload.selectedBrief;
        contextInput.value = payload.projectContext;
        if (sourceInput) sourceInput.value = payload.referenceSource;
      }
      modal.classList.add('is-open');
      document.body.classList.add('bw-header-drawer-open');
    }

    root.querySelectorAll('[data-bw-wardrobe-estimate-open]').forEach(function (button) {
      button.addEventListener('click', function () {
        openModal(button.getAttribute('data-estimate-trigger'));
      });
    });

    chips.forEach(function (chip) {
      chip.addEventListener('click', function (event) {
        var href = chip.getAttribute('href') || '';
        if (!href || href.charAt(0) !== '#') return;
        var target = document.querySelector(href);
        if (!target) return;
        event.preventDefault();
        var chipKey = chip.getAttribute('data-wardrobe-chip');
        var nextUrl = new URL(window.location.href);
        if (chipKey === 'sliding') nextUrl.searchParams.set('type', 'Sliding');
        else if (chipKey === 'hinged') nextUrl.searchParams.set('type', 'Hinged');
        else if (chipKey === 'walk-in') nextUrl.searchParams.set('type', 'Walk-in');
        else nextUrl.searchParams.delete('type');
        setCurrentChip(chipKey);
        nextUrl.hash = href.replace('#', '');
        window.history.replaceState({}, '', nextUrl.pathname + nextUrl.search + nextUrl.hash);
        persistPlanningPayload('type-select');
        target.scrollIntoView({ behavior: 'smooth', block: 'start' });
      });
    });

    root.querySelectorAll('a[href="#wardrobe-calculator"]').forEach(function (link) {
      link.addEventListener('click', function (event) {
        var target = root.querySelector('#wardrobe-calculator');
        if (!target) return;
        event.preventDefault();
        var calculatorRoot = target.querySelector('[data-bw-wardrobe-flow]');
        if (calculatorRoot) {
          calculatorRoot.dispatchEvent(new CustomEvent('bw:wardrobe-type-select', {
            detail: { type: wardrobeTypeForCalculator() }
          }));
        }
        var nextUrl = new URL(window.location.href);
        var currentType = wardrobeTypeForCalculator();
        if (currentType && currentType !== 'all') nextUrl.searchParams.set('type', currentType);
        else nextUrl.searchParams.delete('type');
        setCurrentChip('calculator');
        nextUrl.hash = 'wardrobe-calculator';
        window.history.replaceState({}, '', nextUrl.pathname + nextUrl.search + nextUrl.hash);
        persistPlanningPayload('calculator-jump');
        target.scrollIntoView({ behavior: 'smooth', block: 'start' });
      });
    });

    modal.querySelectorAll('[data-bw-estimate-close]').forEach(function (control) {
      control.addEventListener('click', closeModal);
    });

    window.addEventListener('hashchange', function () {
      setCurrentChip(chipFromHash());
    });
    window.addEventListener('popstate', function () {
      setCurrentChip(chipFromHash());
    });

    setCurrentChip(chipFromHash());
    persistPlanningPayload('landing');
  })();
</script>
